  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cc9f1928",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This establishes a level asymmetry in the price: a short system has unbounded\n",
    "upside through scarcity pricing, whereas a long system is floored near zero or\n",
    "slightly negative. It is the bounded vs unbounded shape of imbalance pricing.\n",
    "\n",
    "The gamma term captures something separate the conditional-variance\n",
    "recursion: whether a shock of a given sign raises next period's volatility more\n",
    "than an equal-sized shock of the opposite sign. In this case, gamma is positive (0.40) and\n",
    "loads on the negative residuals, which are the system-long/oversupplied periods. So for a\n",
    "shock of equal magnitude, an oversupply shock raises subsequent conditional\n",
    "volatility more than a scarcity shock does. The fragility sits near the curtailment and\n", 
    "negative-pricing thresholds where small movements in NIV flip the system across a boundary.\n",
    "\n",
    "The two asymmetries therefore point to opposite sides of the imbalance. Scarcity\n",
    "carries the highest price levels and the unbounded tail where as oversupply carries the\n",
    "greater volatility loading. The positive gamma is not a conventional scarcity\n",
    "effect but instead a representation of long-system fragility."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "346a67c5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 7. Standardised residual diagnostics\n",
    "\n",
    "As a final check, the standardised residuals are inspected for remaining\n",
    "structure. If the variance model is adequate, the clustering visible earlier in\n",
    "the squared residuals should be largely removed."
   ]
